# When to use {{ display_name }}

A decision guide for architects and engineering managers. No vendor grid; just the shape of the fit and the shape of the misfit, with reasoning.

## The shape {{ display_name }} is for

You have a database (or several — possibly of different engines). You have consumers who want to read from it. You want:

- A uniform HTTP surface that speaks JSON.
- Consumers who don't need DB drivers, DB credentials, or SQL skills beyond "filter rows on a column."
- A consistent audit point (one place logs every query) rather than direct DB connections scattered across clients.
- Read-only by construction on the dynamic `/{schema}/{table}` surface — not by policy that someone could forget to apply. Operator-authored custom queries under `/queries/*` are safe-by-review rather than safe-by-construction; see [security-posture.md](security-posture.md) for the distinction.
- A tight enough API surface that you don't have to review every consumer's query to feel comfortable.

If most of that resonates, {{ display_name }} is likely a reasonable fit.

## Strong fits

**Internal data-platform teams.** You run a warehouse or a reporting replica, and you have many internal consumers — dashboards, notebooks, analysts' scripts, other services' background jobs. You don't want each of them installing a database driver, managing their own credentials, or writing their own HTTP wrappers. One {{ display_name }} per DB, a gateway in front, and every consumer talks HTTP.

**Cross-engine estates.** You're operating Oracle in one business unit, Postgres in another, a Trino lakehouse for analytics, and consumers have to move between them. {{ display_name }} gives you an identical API shape across all five supported engines. A client written against the Postgres {{ display_name }} works against the Oracle {{ display_name }} with only a URL change. The value is the *consistency*, not any one engine.

**Lakehouse-to-HTTP gateway.** You run Trino for federated analytics. Consumers want query access but shouldn't install a Trino client or hold Trino credentials. {{ display_name }} in front of Trino gives them `GET /catalog.schema.table?...` URLs with the same safety properties as any other variant.

**"Everyone needs a read model" situations.** Microservices each have their own DB, and each team keeps getting the same ask: "can you give us an HTTP endpoint for that table?" Put {{ display_name }} in front of each service's read replica, publish the URL pattern, and delete the pile of one-off GET endpoints teams have been maintaining.

## Weak fits

**You need writes.** {{ display_name }} is read-only by construction. If your consumers need to create or update rows, you need a different tool. You *can* run {{ display_name }} for reads and a separate service for writes, but at that point question whether a uniform API over your DB is actually what you want, or whether you want an application.

**You need the full expressive power of SQL to be available at the URL.** {{ display_name }}'s closed grammar is small on purpose. If your analysts are expected to write `LIKE '%foo%'`, `CASE WHEN`, window functions, or dynamic joins from the URL, {{ display_name }} will frustrate them. Custom queries (YAML) cover the cases where operators can pre-define the shape, but if consumers need to author arbitrary SQL, give them SQL — a notebook, a BI tool, a query console.

**You need a GraphQL-ish federated query layer.** {{ display_name }} does not stitch. One table per request. One custom-query file per pre-built joined view. If you want `{ orders { customer { ... } lineItems { ... } } }` automatically federated across services, use GraphQL.

**You need sub-10ms p99 for hot paths.** {{ display_name }} does one DB round-trip per request. There's no caching layer, no materialization, no precomputed responses. If your use case is "serve this lookup 50k times a second at p99=5ms," put a cache in front of {{ display_name }}, or don't use {{ display_name }} for that path.

**You need streaming.** Responses are buffered JSON. Pagination works, but a 10M-row scan will happily buffer 10M rows in memory at `$count=10000000`. Set `MAX_PAGE_SIZE` and design clients to paginate.

**You need Postgres-specific things over the wire.** {{ display_name }} returns JSON rows, not Postgres binary protocol. No `COPY`, no listen/notify, no native array types as anything other than their JSON-serialized forms. If you need those, connect to Postgres directly.

## Posture-level comparison to alternatives

This is not a feature grid. It's how {{ display_name }} positions against the options architects typically weigh it against, at the level that matters for the adoption decision.

### vs. letting clients connect directly to the DB

Direct connections give consumers maximum flexibility — they can write any SQL. That's the thing {{ display_name }} is trading away. In exchange:

- One place logs every query.
- No database driver installed at the consumer.
- Credentials don't need to be handed out (or are scoped per-consumer via passthrough, with {{ display_name }}'s validation bounding what they can ask for even if their credentials would allow more).
- Read-only by construction — not by granting `SELECT`-only and hoping.
- A uniform API across multiple DB engines.

You'd pick direct connections when consumers are a small number of trusted callers who actually need SQL flexibility. You'd pick {{ display_name }} when consumers are numerous, diverse, or semi-trusted, and the flexibility tax is worth the operational consistency.

### vs. hand-written REST endpoints (Flask / Express / etc.)

Every time someone asks "can you expose an endpoint for table X" and you build a new Flask route, you're writing variations on the same theme: validate params, build SQL, serialize, paginate, handle errors. {{ display_name }} is that work, done once.

The real difference is not effort — it's consistency and boundary. A hand-written endpoint has whatever safety properties its author remembered. {{ display_name }} has the same safety properties for every endpoint automatically: identifiers validated, literals bound, writes impossible. Consumers get the same URL shape for every table instead of every team inventing their own.

You'd pick hand-written endpoints when the endpoint needs to do real work — business logic, transformations, writes, composition. You'd pick {{ display_name }} when the endpoint is genuinely "give me rows from this table, with some filters."

### vs. Hasura, PostgREST, Supabase's REST API

These are also "HTTP in front of a database." They go further than {{ display_name }}: richer query grammars, write support, GraphQL, auth plumbing, subscriptions.

{{ display_name }} is deliberately narrower:

- Read-only. No writes at all. No chance of a misconfigured policy allowing a write.
- Closed filter grammar. No `LIKE` or function calls at the URL layer. The consumer can only ask for shapes the grammar can express.
- Cross-engine. PostgREST is Postgres. Hasura is Postgres/MySQL/SQL Server/BigQuery with different feature levels per engine. {{ display_name }}'s five variants (Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, Oracle, Trino) have the same feature set everywhere.
- Small. A few thousand lines of Python. The feature set fits in your head.

You'd pick Hasura or PostgREST when their richer feature set (writes, subscriptions, deep relational queries) is what you want and their posture fits your risk tolerance. You'd pick {{ display_name }} when your requirements are actually read-only and you want the smaller surface — both for review and for the bounded-API guarantee it gives you.

### vs. building a BI tool's API

Tools like Cube or dbt Semantic Layer expose metrics/dimensions over HTTP. That's a different shape of problem: they're giving you semantic modelling, caching, and aggregation pipelines.

{{ display_name }} is just "rows from this table" — no modelling layer, no cache, no metrics DSL. If your consumers want curated metrics (`total_revenue_by_region_by_month`), a semantic layer is the right tool. If they want to read rows, {{ display_name }} is lighter and cheaper.

### vs. a message bus / CDC stream

For "keep my system in sync with changes in their DB," use CDC (Debezium, native logical replication, etc.). {{ display_name }} gives you point-in-time reads; it doesn't give you change events.

## Decision shortcuts

Answer these four questions. If any is "yes" to the first column, lean {{ display_name }}. If any is "yes" to the second column, {{ display_name }} is probably the wrong choice.

| Lean {{ display_name }} | Lean away |
|---|---|
| Read-only access | You need writes |
| Many internal consumers, small DB team | Small number of sophisticated consumers who need SQL |
| Heterogeneous DB estate | Single DB that matches a richer tool's sweet spot (Postgres → PostgREST) |
| Safety-first posture; bounded API | Need `LIKE`, window functions, aggregations across tables at the URL |
| Happy with "one request, one table" | Need composed / federated queries over a graph |

## The honest caveats

{{ display_name }}'s closed grammar is an opinion. Consumers who've used richer "OData" or Hasura-style APIs will initially find it restrictive. The response to that is custom queries: operators pre-build the shapes consumers need, and consumers parameterize them. This works well when there's a small-to-medium set of reusable analytical shapes. It works badly when every consumer wants a fundamentally different query.

The lack of caching is also an opinion. A request always hits the DB. If you want caching you're building another layer. That's sometimes fine and sometimes annoying.

The DDL cache being in-memory and harvested at startup is convenient but means schema changes require a ping or a restart. Most teams don't change schemas often enough for this to matter, but a team doing rapid schema evolution will want to automate the re-harvest.

## Where {{ display_name }} fits best

Best uses, in our view:

- Behind an API gateway that terminates TLS, enforces auth, and rate-limits — {{ display_name }} handling the "translate URL to safe SQL" job and nothing else.
- As a replacement for a pile of hand-rolled GET endpoints that all do the same thing slightly differently.
- As the read API for internal-facing data products where the consumers are many, the DB count is plural, and the safety/consistency property is worth more than flexibility.

Worst uses, in our view:

- As a public API. It's fine *behind* a public gateway, but the stock manifests don't ship TLS, rate limiting, or a full auth stack. The presumption is that something else does those.
- As the write path for anything.
- As the backend for a feature-rich BI tool. The grammar is too narrow.
- When you'd have to build a dozen custom queries to cover consumer needs. At that point you're writing a query service; write a query service.

If you're somewhere on the boundary — "we want this but maybe we need a bit more" — lean toward trying {{ display_name }} for the read paths you have and keeping a separate purpose-built service for the things {{ display_name }} doesn't do. Don't bend {{ display_name }} to cover cases it isn't shaped for. The narrowness is the value.
